section.section:
The Department, in consultation with the Office of the Attorney General, shall develop an information sheet that provides information relating to advance directives, which shall include:
Written statements informing an individual that an advance directive:
Is a useful, legal, and well established way for an individual to direct medical care;
Allows an individual to specify the medical care that the individual will receive and can alleviate conflict among family members and health care providers;
Can ensure that an individual's religious beliefs are considered when directing medical care;
Is most effective if completed in consultation with family members, or legal and religious advisors, if an individual desires;
Can be revoked or changed at any time;
Is available in many forms, including model forms developed by religious organizations, estate planners, and lawyers;
Does not have to be on any specific form and can be personalized; and
If completed, should be copied for an individual's family members, physicians, and legal advisors; and
The following written statements:
That an individual should discuss the appointment of a health care agent with the potential appointee;
That advance directives are for individuals of all ages;
That in the absence of an appointed health care agent, the next of kin make an individual's health care decisions when the individual is incapable of making those decisions; and
That an individual is not required to complete an advance directive.
